<item>
            <title>[KAFKA-1096] An old controller coming out of long GC could update its epoch to the latest controller&apos;s epoch</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-1096</link>
                <project id="12311720" key="KAFKA">Kafka</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;If a controller GCs for too long, we could have two controllers in the cluster. The controller epoch is supposed to minimize the damage in such a situation, as the brokers will reject the requests sent by the controller with an older epoch.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When the old controller is still in long GC, a new controller could be elected. This will fire ControllerEpochListener on the old controller. When it comes out of GC, its ControllerEpochListener will update its own epoch to the new controller&apos;s epoch. So both controllers are now able to send out requests with the same controller epoch until the old controller&apos;s handleNewSession() can execute in the controller lock. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ControllerEpochListener does not seem necessary, so we can probably delete it.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
